<br>
Now, any computer program can only do what it is told.  In a game like everquest, there are saftey measures programmed in.  For example, a max time limit put on the sleepers rampage so that it doesn't continue to run around forever.  That would be reasonable to believe.  My question is simple - why is it that the sleeper stayed up more than 3 and a half hours on other servers rampaging around?  As a matter of fact, I believe I spent more time than that on Xev waiting for it to show up in SS while people kept zoning into ST to see what it would do.<br>
<br>
It is possible it was a combination of the warders trying to respawn and the extended time of the script that reset it.  It is possible that it could have been many things - EQ has some very complicated code.<br>
<br>
However, think about a couple of things.  1) It was not just the sleeper who despawned - all pets in the zone respawned as well.  I have only ever seen my pet despawn automatically twice before - BOTH times involved a full zone reset done by a GM.  2) The 4th warder repopped - that has not happened on any other server when the sleeper despawned to my knowledge.  3)  There have been several reports that the GM present gave a reason to people that HE despawned he sleeper. 4) The parties in question are beng offered 2 AA and loss of exp back - something I have never heard of being done for a bugged encounter which are far more common than you'd believe.  High end guilds deal with these all the time.  FoH, AL, and others virtually beta tested VT, Time, the Elemental Plans, ect.  Sony has a record of intentionally sabotaging an encounter they are not ready for a guild to beat.<br>
<br>
All of these amount to nothing more than circumstantial evidence.  However, put together, I still think it points to a GM following orders and Sony realizing what type of shitstorm this would kick up and covering their bases.  They provide a technically viable solution that can never be verified and allow another chance.<br>
<br>
Now, let me clarify this by saying that even if I am right - Sony did the right thing in this case.  While I think they have really dropped the ball in the past, this is a decent action.  Therefore - whatever the motive for their action, they should be given the benefit of the doubt in this case.<br>
<br>
Xalion Buscador <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=usildordhujata>Usildor Dhujata</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Crypt Pimp</span><br>  Posts: 1255<br> <font color=#330000>(11/17/03 4:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1140.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/poeticsarcasm/images/marblemn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: NOZ !</span><hr size=1> Oh I'm giving more than the benefit of the doubt.  I think the reaction is wonderful (putting sleeper back, giving 2 AA's and fixing it and giving them another go at it).  I'm just saying that people have every right to jump down the GMs throats even if the GM didnt reset the zone (which you have pointed out very well they most probably did) because of the past BS we've been forced to deal with.  This wasnt simply a bug, it was poor programming and/or a deliberate GM sabotage.  Either way it sucks for the gamer and the GMs are there to take the heat.    But yah Xalion I agree with you 100%, it's pretty obvious what happened.  But at least they are being fair and helping the players out and letting them have another chance (only took 8000 petitions) instead of past responses along the lines of &quot;uh well we're sorry, we fixed it now&quot;....this time they made a smart move at least.  So kudos on that I guess. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
