<br>
I have no idea how it's all implemented on the server side, but I think that due to the zone orientated structure of the server it would it unlikely the the sleeper was one individual script (which would require it to be outside any 'Zone' program) More likely, it is implemented that all the scripts are in each zone's program, with simply one interface function, or whatever they have to trigger the next. So instead of having one script for sleepers, skyshrine, ww and whatever, you have several different scripts, with an easy 'trigger' from one zone to the next.<br>
<br>
Here the time limit makes sense, and is quite an easy thing to take into account to make sure bad things don't happen.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>One problem Ram, it isn't impossible and never was. If it was, it would have been written in such a way that you could never damage it, it would never move below 99%.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I have heard not one, single peice of evidence from any player on any server that had ever said that killing the sleeper was possible. I'd pressume that this has been the case up to one month or less ago.<br>
<br>
It's like saying for 2 years that going faster than the speed of sound is impossible, then shouting how you knew it was for many years.<br>
<br>
Now, the 'They should have known about it' attitude, is rather cute, but as a programmer, I'll tell you it is absolutley impossible.<br>
<br>
For example, a month ago, I was designing and writing a peice of software to test a GPIB Regression system for a product my company designs, it's purely for in-house development intended to make it easy to tell what random things we screw up with a parituclar code modification.<br>
<br>
Someone came up to me 2 weeks ago and asked if it would work for another product we designed. The answer was that it didn't, because I'd tailored the system to work for another system, but with some minor changes, it worked.<br>
<br>
I can name another dozen times in the last 6 months this has happened. <br>
<br>
You have to. HAVE to, make assumptions when writing programs. If someone breaks those assumptions, you have to go back, and re-do software.<br>
<br>
This program worked. It did everything it was supposed to do, it solved our exact problem and fullfilled everything it needed to. Until.....<br>
<br>
SOMEONE TRIED TO DO SOMETHING THAT WAS NOT INTENDED BY THE PROGRAM.<br>
<br>
This isn't my fault, It worked, It did everything I, and everyone else wanted to, I didn't think about it, because no-one had challenged my assumption.<br>
<br>
Telling me I should have gone back to analyse what went on, and that I should have known what would have happened is like saying I need to know everything that could possibly ever change in the future.<br>
<br>
Thats called reading the future, and is something I do not do.<br>
<br>
What I do, however, is make it so that any changes are easy to make, and try and deal with things ahead of time. I gaurentee you that for every situation where this type of thing has happened to me, I have written a dozen peices of code where I have allowed for something along those lines.<br>
<br>
Now, the thing is, that that analogy only works if the person who wrote the scipt is the same guy who fixed it. but...<br>
<br>
Now, another analogy that I think would be particularily apt, <br>
<br>
I was recently working on function for the same program, that used GPIB (a remote interface, like RS232, or Ethernet) to transfer massive amounts of data from this machine to my PC.<br>
<br>
I had enourmous amounts of problems trying to do this, as each time I attempted to do so, an error was thrown (thanks to the program, the machine kept on running with 0 problems, it just meant the function didn't work).<br>
<br>
The problem stemmed from a simple assumption a guy who no longer works for my company made almost 2 years ago.<br>
<br>
He assumed that I would not be trying to send more than 512 bytes of data at once. Thats a fair assumption as the most data sent in one block from this machine is about 50 bytes. <br>
<br>
I had not paid any attention to this assumption, because It worked, I had no problem with it, and it did everything I wanted to.<br>
<br>
I only realised the assumption was fundamentally false because I had tried to do something that broke it.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, you will say it's obvious that the sleeper would have been killable. I call bullshit. <br>
<br>
Everquest is probably many, many powers of ten larger in terms of code size than the software I am writing for this machine. Expecting every single person, or even any single person to always question the validity of assumptions designed into the program is ridiculous, and foolish.<br>
<br>
I will always work out that some assumptions are false, and should be rectified ahead of time, I have done and will continue to do so. <br>
<br>
A Software team, will never, ever, ever, ever be able to isolate every single false assumption before they are prooved false. Ever.<br>
<br>
The more mundane the assumption is, the less likely they are to proove false.<br>
<br>
Your seat belt analogy is flawed, because it was actually discovered the same way, because people died, not because they worked out the seat belt needed upgrading before.<br>
<br>
A simpler analogy to proove my summation.<br>
<br>
<br>
If you walk into your house, and try to turn on the lightbulb, and it doesn't light up, you do a quick check to see if the lights are on in the house (hence not a power failure) then check the light bulb to see if it's blown, then check the fuse.<br>
<br>
You have assumed up to now, it will turn on.<br>
<br>
What you are suggesting, is before you switch on the light, you check to see if the lights are on in your house, check the bulb, check the fuse, THEN switch on the light.<br>
<br>
It is neither practical, nor even possible to do this, saying otherwise is idiotic.<br>
<br>
<br>
A final Summary<br>
<br>
Good programming is not making a system work for every concievable situation all of the time with no work, because that would require so much time as to be stupid.<br>
<br>
Good programming is making the system work with any concievable change with the minimum amount of effort. Which, correct me if I'm wrong, was what has happened here.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
