1)&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Some GM decided (as a renegade OR under orders) that Sleeper would not be killed, so he laughed manically as he repopped the zone, then watched as the entire zerg force was wiped out.  When he was done, he sat back and popped open a root beer to celebrate.<br>
2)&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp There was a problem (or perhaps problems) in the script. <br>
3)&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp SoE write Sleeper so it would only last 3.5 hours after it started the rampage.  Knowing that nobody would kill it, and knowing that walking indefinitely would only make people never go to Vellious again, they took action to help prevent this.  After 3.5 hours … no more sleeper.  If this is the case .. everything was working fine.<br>
4)&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp We dreamed the whole thing.<br>
<br>
Except for 1 and 4, I am willing to believe this.  Let’s SUPOSE the GM had not poofed sleeper, and let’s PRETEND it passed the 3 hour limit with no despawn.  Just for fun, pretend that the warders popped in and something, ANYTHING went wrong and the zerg force started to fall apart.  If Sleeper gets out there is no safeguard (since the three hour limit has passed) and Sleeper will just walk along killing everything for as long as (s)he likes.<br>
<br>
I/m not a programmer, I wouldn’t pretend to be, but I have a very minimal understanding of the complexities we are dealing with here.  The reason the GMs are able to repop a zone is because some programmer (team of programmers, probably) installed a switch that allows them to do it.  Reason, safeguard.  It is a fast easy way to reset a zone without having to go blind digging through script … OR a easy way to reset a zone after you already HAVE.  <br>
It sounds to me like the Sleeper script wasn’t working.  SOMETHING happened and it wasn’t functioning properly and after the allotted time, the GM knew that he/she would have to repop the zone to prevent a massacre of any NONuber person that still wants to PLAY Everquest… instead of simply dominating anything that crosses their path.<br>
<br>
Now I am making a LOT of guesses here, but when I try to think of the number  of variables involved in this game, it’s mind blowing.  JUST between faction, vendors, skills, weapons abilities, and enough bool switches to make a calculator want to shit its microchips, you are talking about more variables than I would EVER EVER want to deal with.  This isn’t the work of one lazy programmer, this is hundreds of programmers doing the best they can so we can play a video game.  To think that they can dig through this MONOLITH of a program to find individual bugs is sadistic.<br>
Now, I agree, if they didn’t want Sleeper to be killed, they should have made sleeper impossible to engage.  They didn’t. When they wrote Sleeper, there probably was NO fucking way in HELL any team of people could kill it, so they didn’t bother.<br>
Now, YEARS later, and 3, 4, 5(?) expansions later some of you have the people, the abilities and the gear that can take this best down.  Unfortunately for you … MOST of us don’t.  Don’t sit there telling me what a minority I am because I still want to enjoy playing this game instead of seeing how high I can get my numbers.  I do /whoall (class) 65 from time to time just to se how many there are.  Yeah, there are a lot more now than there were a year ago, but there STILL aren’t NEAR as many as there are on lower levels.  If you aren’t showing up on a /whoall, then whatever, but you will NOT convince me that you are the majority when I overflow on lower ranks and almost NEVER overflow on 65s in ANY class.  If the game isn’t hard enough for you , fucking wah.  Start a new toon and level him/her up the old fashioned way.  No exploits, No twinking, No Pling… straight playing.  Trust me, if you actually want to PLAY the game, there is still plenty to see.<br>
From what I have seen so far, Sleeper did EXACTLY what sleeper was supposed to do.  I remember when it was woken on our server, and 3.5 hours later (roughly speaking) it despawned.  That there is a safeguard written into the script for this makes perfect sense to me, and just adds another dimension to the fight.  You have 3.5 hours to kill it.<br>
FURTHERMORE… if you think you can break into that code and clean up their mistakes and bugs, by ALL means, please do.  I still struggle with flash when I bother with it… and that to EQ is like Legos to a rocket scientist.  I might not agree with what happened, and yeah, I think RZ got fucked.  BUT … I think you are acting like a bunch of old women by sitting here bitching about it.<br>
You tell me I have been heard, well, so have YOU.  So god damn much, as a matter of a fact, that I threadjacked a thread EXACTLY like this last time you fuckers wouldn’t quit bitching about it.  If I remember correctly, YOU, Usildor, were one of the ones asking people to chill out and let it go.  <br>
The GMs did more in this case than I have ever heard of a GM doing before.  You DARE sit there and say that you fault them because their programming doesn’t meet your strict standards?  Give me a fucking break!  I am SURE that if you can fix it, they will be HAPPY to hire you so to do.<br>
Of course, I KNOW You said you aren’t a programmer.  In that case, I find it the biggest load of smoking horseshit that you have the balls to fault them for it.  GMs can’t just take action, everything they do has to go through an unreal system of checks, and their hands are usually tied.  Do you have any idea how enormous this game is?  You talk about it like it is some program written in basic:<br>
<br>
10 CLS<br>
20 Print “EQ is Cool”<br>
30 goto 10<br>
40 end<br>
<br>
… oops, forgot the ;. <br>
<br>
Trust me, it is a bit more complicated.  There are probably more variables controlling the appearance of ONE TOON than you have ever dealt with in your life.  Yeah, when we hit a bug, they can go back and fix it.  Once we trip over it, they can identify it and go fix it.  I wouldn’t expect them to be able to look at it and KNOW where all the mistakes are.  That is just an unreal expectation.<br>
<br>
Your comparison with the car is a good one, but far too simple.  This is more like figuring out the genetic code for Kwip… then trying to change one variable so he isn’t such a lame fucktard.<br>
Yeah, MAYBE it is possible… but would YOU want to get stuck with that job?  I would rather just despawn him after 3.5 hours.<br>
