<br>
You seem to have my examples going over your head.<br>
<br>
I'll give you a better example.<br>
<br>
About 33 years ago, a very large vehicle was upgraded from 24 volts to 42 Volts for purposes of compatability.<br>
<br>
Most aspects of that vehicle were upgraded to work with the higher voltage.<br>
<br>
<br>
One critical part of that vehicle, a thermostat for a heater was not upgraded. This was not a problem on it's own, as it wasn't really big on the scheme of things.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, the error was compounded, because the thermostat wasn't really intended to be used very often, if at all (as it was a cut off for a temperature that was never intended to be exceeded anyway). There was a small problem with a tube near the thermostat that meant that the heaters in the tank the thermostat was at needed to be turned on to heat up and boil off some of the stuff in the tank.<br>
<br>
Now, the thermostat hit the cut off temperature, and fused shut, meaning the temperature of the tank was never regulated, and it just kept heating up and heating up.<br>
<br>
This would have been okay, but no-one realised that the temperature gauge for that tank didn't go past the maximum intended temperature.<br>
<br>
The temperature of the tank, was so intense, that it burned off all the insulation inside the tank, exposing the wiring for all components inside the tank.<br>
<br>
Four days Later, Jack swigart, pushed a button to perform a Cryogenic stir of the oxygen tanks that this thermostat was regulating, the wiring create a spark, and the oxygen exploded, it took out a chunk of side of the vehicle, and left it without any oxygen for it's 5 day journey around and back from the moon.<br>
<br>
If you hadn't guessed, this Vessel was apollo 13.<br>
<br>
<br>
This sleeper incident, is the same deal.<br>
<br>
In the sleeper, there was one design flaw, two unlikely occourances, and one half likely occourance.<br>
<br>
These are :<br>
<br>
The sleeper despawned after 3 hours, people thought to wake/kill him, he was still spawnable, and that they were still fighting after three hours.<br>
<br>
The particular likelihood of any of these happening are extremely unlikely, if it hadn't been for any single ONE of those incidents, this problem would not have occoured.<br>
<br>
Saying it should have been solved when players reached that particular point, is wishful thinking and hindsight at it's best.<br>
<br>
It's not practicle, and certainly it isn't anyones fault.<br>
<br>
I've been showing how unlikely it was thought to be, how unlikely the programmers are to actually think about it, and how low on the radar it would have been.<br>
<br>
From a programming perspective, I would have expect a million times more things of this sort to happen, in fact, I CAN name a million other things that are the same design and planning wise to this that haven't gone wrong.<br>
<br>
However, the programmers are satan, for thinking of those million but not this unlikely occourance.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
