<br>
Let me explain why - I think some of you misunderstood the events of the night.<br>
<br>
First, the guilds prepared for and woke the sleeper.  Now, this was almost certainly spurred on by a recent attempt by a japanese guild to kill the sleeper.  In their attempt, all 4 warders respawned on them as they got to about 20%.  Just to clear up a lot of crap going around - this was done on an asian server with only velious installed.  So, the Japanese guild killing the sleeper (they did manage this) automatically shoots down a large portion of the arguments I am seeing here - the sleeper was not designed as unkillable - he was designed to get 1 shot.  The japanese guild did it with ONLY velious equipment and experience.<br>
<br>
That being said, the guilds fought for around 3.5 hours.  At this time - SEVERAL things happened.  First, the sleeper despawned.  This by itself is unremarkable - the result of a script.  Second, all pets in the zone despawned.  This is remarkable - I'll get to it later.  Third, the fourth - and only the fourth - warder respawned.  This happened after the sleeper had already despawned.  Fourth, several people have reported being told that the sleeper wasn't to be killed, he was too important from the perspective of EQII.  Note that this was not a &quot;wipe&quot;.  That was the Japanese guild, not the events in question.<br>
<br>
After that got around, a lot of petitions hit Sony.  We then get a paper cutter explanation from Sony - but with actions they have refused to take for nearly 3 years on any other encounter.<br>
<br>
Looking at this from the standpoint of a programmer - we do not know exactly how the script was written.  However, we have numerous examples of the script running on other servers.  It has been known for a long time (ever since they revamped SS) that the script did not function properly.  Take what happened on Xev for instance - the sleeper was up for longer than 3.5 hours - and never got to SS.  Also, look what happened to the pets.  Pets are not affected by scripts running in a zone normally.  The only thing I have seen despawn a pet like that is a zone reset.  Note what I said - a zone reset - not a mob despawn.  You can take the Rallos Zek event as an example - fake Rallos despawns at between 30 and 60% life and the real Rallos respawns.  Pets do not despawn at that time.<br>
<br>
It is possible that at the time Velious was written - this type of dynamic scripting did not exist.  However, every time the sleeper has not been allowed to finish his script by something stopping it from completing that I can think of, he has had to be /killed by a GM.  I can think of at least one instance that he was reset back to his unwoken state because of a bug in the script that didn't allow him to finish.<br>
<br>
Now, I believe the key was the 4th warder.  The 4th warder could have only respawned as part of the script - there is no other explanation for it.  Had the zone just been reset, everything would have respawned.  Had the Sleeper just despawned, the script would have been considered completed and the server wouldn't have respawned him.  <br>
<br>
There are 2 possible explanations for this - first, that the event is not a single script.  That instead, it is a series of scripts.  The script taking care of the sleeper executed.  When he got to a certain percentage life, the script dealing with the 4th warder ran.  He then despawned before the scripts dealing with the 1-3rd warder could run.<br>
<br>
The second explanation is that when the GM saw that they were prepared for the warders and realized they weren't going to wipe, he did a zone reset (either out of panic or following orders) - which stops all scripts from running.  As the sleeper is a 1 time thing, upon the zone reset, server would have registered him as down and left him down.  The 4th warder however very well could have been left up - until the zone updates to the revamped sleeper's tomb, the server has no way to know he is supposed to be down.<br>
<br>
Now, I was not arguing that the programmers are lazy or that their job is easy.  When you get to millions of lines of code, a bug can be incredibly hard to find and when you make a change, you never know what else it might break.  What I am arguing is that those who went off saying Sony is angelic and everyone is paraniod is not looking at the facts.  This would not be the first time Sony has done something like this.  It would only be the most wide reaching (almost everyone wants to see what happens when the sleeper dies - its human nature, we don't believe there is anything that &quot;can't&quot; be done).  Furthermore - Sony has NEVER reacted like this to this type of problem.  If it really was a problem in the script, Sony would have been much more likely to post a public explanation of the script on their front page and leave the RZ folks to deal with it.  However, they had a huge problem.  That explanation does not explain why the GM in question told the guilds involved that it was done intentionally.<br>
<br>
In my mind, the most likely scenario is that a late night GM was watching and told someone (a programmer or lead GM on staff) that the sleeper was going to get beat.  As it was late night, a large portion of the administrative staff wouldn't have been there, and for a game like EQ most certainly wouldn't have been on call.  As this had never been done before and really wasn't envisioned, the person in charge wouldn't have had much in the way of guidelines.  He made a hasty decision, the deed was done and the EQ community blew up.<br>
<br>
The next day when the actual programmers and PR staff arrived, they were met with the shitstorm that had been created.  Between arguments with the programmers of what was supposed to happen and the PR people, they came up with this solution on the fly.  The AA points and exp regain will make the guilds involved happy and forget anything the GM on staff that night might have said (admit it, people in large groups are sheep.  Toss them a bone and they'll forget all wrongs).  They then reset the script.<br>
<br>
I imagine most of the programmers would actually love to see the sleeper killed.  Why?  Well, then they have a model for the next expansion's ultimate boss.  I think they are more than secure in the knowledge that if they wanted too - they could make an unbeatable encounter.<br>
<br>
Either explanation could have happened - we'll never know.  One way or another, maybe this will change the way they treat the top guilds when they are &quot;beta&quot;ing encounters that have not been tuned nor tested and sometimes, not even finished.<br>
<br>
Xalion Buscador <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=usildordhujata>Usildor Dhujata</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Crypt Pimp</span><br>  Posts: 1258<br> <font color=#330000>(11/17/03 8:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1140.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/poeticsarcasm/images/marblemn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: NOZ !</span><hr size=1> Again Ram all I'm saying is that with the level of DPS and gear of today, I feel Sony should have been ready.  Sleeper should have been updated for PoP.  Lots of entire zones have been revamped.  The Sleeper is their one big major mob.  It's not some little guage on a heater...one out of 200,000 more major moving parts.  This is the only mob never beaten.  It's a crown jewel.  I refuse to believe that it never got into anybody's head at SoE &quot;well, if we're inventing 5 more levels, more spells and AA's, increasing max dps output by X%....what happens when the next zerg fest goes after sleeper?&quot;  Sure, some of the less major zones had to be revamped after a while.  I dont expect attention to every detail.  But failure to look at the sleeper scenario is more like failing to replace the electrical fuses of the control panel on a spacecraft, not the guage for one of the heaters.  We can agree to disagree.  I dont expect perfection like I said, but I expect reasonable.  And this wasnt some miniboss in a pre-luclin zone.  This was the fuckin sleeper.  I dont believe the thought never occured to them, and if it didn't....that's even worse.  And as Xalion has done a good job of pointing out, the whole script error thing sure looks like a crock of shit.  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER STAR